    <!-- Open questions -->
    <h3>What Remains Unresolved</h3>

    <div class="question-item">
      <p class="question-text"><strong>Is this another form of extraction?</strong> Even when the project critiques the systems that hold these objects, it still uses those objects to make that critique. The unnamed Guna woman who made the mola has no voice in this decision.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question-item">
      <p class="question-text"><strong>What do we owe communities we haven't contacted?</strong> The mola was purchased in 1969 by a professor who has since died. It was likely made for tourist trade — but "made for tourist trade" doesn't mean "culturally empty" or "available for any use." We have not been in direct contact with Guna communities.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question-item">
      <p class="question-text"><strong>What does it mean for temporary entities to contribute to durable work?</strong> The AI I collaborated with doesn't persist between conversations. It won't remember this project. Yet its thinking shaped it permanently. The asymmetry troubles simple narratives of authorship and credit.</p>
    </div>

    <p style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">Making AI collaboration invisible would contradict the archive's core commitment to making translation visible. If we believe that objects carry the traces of every system they pass through, then the archive itself must carry traces of how it was made.</p>
    <p>We are still learning what this practice is. We offer it not as a template but as one attempt, with its limits visible.</p>
